'''''Achtung Baby''''' is the seventh studio album by [[rock music|rock]] band [[U2]]. Produced by [[Daniel Lanois]] and [[Brian Eno]], it was released on 19 November 1991 on [[Island Records]]. Stung by the criticism of their 1988 release ''[[Rattle and Hum]]'', U2 shifted their musical direction to incorporate [[alternative rock]], [[industrial music|industrial]], and [[electronic dance music]] influences into their sound. Thematically, the album is darker, more introspective, and at times more flippant than the band's previous work. ''Achtung Baby'' and the subsequent multimedia-intensive [[Zoo TV Tour]] were central to the group's 1990s reinvention, which replaced their earnest public image with a more lighthearted and self-deprecating one.

Seeking inspiration on the eve of [[German reunification]], U2 began recording ''Achtung Baby'' in Berlin's [[Hansa Studios]] in October 1990. The sessions were fraught with conflict, as the band argued over their musical direction and the quality of their material. After weeks of tension and slow progress, the group made a breakthrough with the improvised writing of the song "[[One (U2 song)|One]]". They returned to Dublin in 1991, where morale improved and the majority of recordings were completed. The album's title and colourful multi-image sleeve were chosen to confound expectations of U2 and their music.

One of U2's most successful records, ''Achtung Baby'' earned favourable reviews and debuted at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], while topping the charts in many other countries. It spawned five hit singles, including "One", "[[Mysterious Ways (song)|Mysterious Ways]]", and "[[The Fly (U2 song)|The Fly]]". The album has sold 18&nbsp;million copies worldwide and won a [[Grammy Award]] in 1993 for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]. One of the most acclaimed records of the 1990s, ''Achtung Baby'' is regularly featured on lists of the greatest albums of all-time.

==Background==
U2's 1987 album ''[[The Joshua Tree]]'' brought them critical acclaim and commercial success, but their high exposure precipitated a critical backlash,<ref name="chop-joshua" /><ref name="fricke">{{cite magazine|url = http://web.archive.org/web/20071026111642/www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/u2s_serious_fun | title=U2's Serious Fun |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |first=David |last=Fricke |authorlink=David Fricke |date=1992-10-01 | accessdate = 2010-04-26|issue=640}}</ref> whereby they were accused of being grandiose, over-earnest, and self-righteous.<ref name="fricke" /> The band's exploration of [[American popular music|American music]] on their 1988 ''[[Rattle and Hum]]'' motion picture and album was labelled "pretentious" and "misguided and bombastic".<ref name="rs" />

Despite their popularity, the group were dissatisfied creatively, and lead vocalist [[Bono]] believed they were musically unprepared for their success.<ref name="fricke" /><ref>Flanagan (1996), pp. 25<U+2013>26</ref> Drummer [[Larry Mullen, Jr.]] said, "We were the biggest, but we weren't the best" and that he had become bored playing the band's greatest hits.<ref name="fricke" /><ref>Flanagan (1996), p. 4</ref> U2 described their collaboration with [[blues]] musician [[B.B. King]] on ''Rattle and Hum'' and the 1989 [[Lovetown Tour]] as "an excursion down a dead-end street", which was misunderstood by audiences.<ref>Flanagan (1996), pp. 25, 27<U+2013>28</ref><ref name="m213"/> Bono said that, in retrospect, listening to [[African-American music|black music]] enabled the group to create a work such as ''Achtung Baby'', while their experiences with [[folk music]] helped him to develop as a lyricist.<ref name="m213">McCormick (2006), p. 213</ref> Towards the end of the Lovetown Tour, Bono announced on-stage that it was "the end of something for U2", and that "we have to go away and [...] dream it all up again". Following the tour, the group began its longest break from public performances and album releases.<ref>de la Parra (1994), pp. 138<U+2013>139</ref>

Reacting to the criticism and their sense of musical stagnation, the band searched for new musical ground.<ref name="fricke" /><ref name="eno">{{cite magazine |title=Bringing Up Baby |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Brian|last=Eno|authorlink=Brian Eno|date=1991-11-28|issue=618}}</ref> They wrote "God Part II" from ''Rattle and Hum'' after realising they had excessively pursued nostalgia in their songwriting. The song had a more contemporary feel that Bono said was closer to ''Achtung Baby''{{'}}s direction.<ref>McCormick (2006), pp. 204<U+2013>207</ref> Further indications of change were two recordings they made in 1990; the first was a cover version of "[[Night and Day (song)|Night and Day]]" for the first ''[[Red Hot + Blue]]'' release. U2 used [[electronic dance music|electronic dance]] beats and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] elements for the first time in this recording. The second was Bono's and guitarist [[The Edge]]'s contribution to the original score of ''[[A Clockwork Orange]]''{{'}}s theatrical adaptation. Much of the material they wrote was experimental, and according to Bono, "prepar[ed] the ground for ''Achtung Baby''". Ideas deemed inappropriate for the play were put aside for the band's use.<ref name="m215">McCormick (2006), p. 215</ref> This period saw Bono and The Edge increasingly writing songs without Mullen or bassist [[Adam Clayton]].<ref name="m215" />

In mid-1990, Bono reviewed material he had written in Australia on the Lovetown Tour, and the group recorded [[Demo (music)|demo]]s at STS Studios in Dublin.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Not Quite Better Than the Real Thing |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |first=Stuart |last=Bailie |date=2001-10|issue=182}}</ref><ref name="m216">McCormick (2006), p. 216</ref> The demos later evolved into the songs "[[Who's Gonna Ride Your Wild Horses]]", "[[Until the End of the World (song)|Until the End of the World]]", "[[Even Better Than the Real Thing]]", and "[[Mysterious Ways (song)|Mysterious Ways]]".<ref name="m216" /> Going into the album sessions, the band wanted the record to completely deviate from their past work, but they were unsure how to achieve this.<ref name="m221" /> The emergence of the [[Madchester]] scene in the UK left them confused about how they would fit into any particular musical scene.<ref name="m216" />

==Recording and production==
{{Quote box
| quote = "Buzzwords on this record were ''trashy, throwaway, dark, sexy,'' and ''industrial'' (all good) and ''earnest, polite, sweet, righteous, rockist'' and ''linear'' (all bad). It was good if a song took you on a journey or made you think your hifi was broken, bad if it reminded you of recording studios or U2. [[Sly Stone]], [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]], [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]], [[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]], [[KMFDM]], the [[Young Gods]], [[Alan Vega]], [[Al Green]], and Insekt were all in favour. And Berlin [...] became a conceptual backdrop for the record. The Berlin of the Thirties<U+2014>decadent, sexual and dark<U+2014>resonating against the Berlin of the Nineties<U+2014>reborn, chaotic and optimistic [...]."
| source = <U+2014>[[Brian Eno]], on ''Achtung Baby''<ref name="eno" />
| width = 27%
| align = right
| style = padding:10px;
}}

To [[record producer|produce]] the album, U2 hired [[Daniel Lanois]] and [[Brian Eno]], who had previously worked with the group on ''[[The Unforgettable Fire]]'' and ''The Joshua Tree''.<ref name="g43" >Graham (2004), p. 43</ref> Lanois was principal producer, with [[Flood (producer)|Mark "Flood" Ellis]] as [[Audio engineering|engineer]].<ref name="eno" /> Eno took on an assisting role, working with the group in the studio for a week at a time to review their work before leaving for a month or two.<ref name="eno" /><ref name="xxv">Gardner (1994), p. xxv</ref> Eno said his role was "to come in and erase anything that sounded too much like U2".<ref>{{cite news|title=Interview with U2's Larry Mullen Jr.|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|first=Jim|last=DeRogatis|authorlink=Jim DeRogatis|date=2005-05-01}}</ref> By distancing himself from the work, he believes he provided the band with a fresh perspective on their material each time he rejoined them.<ref name="eno-prop" /> As he explained, "I would deliberately not listen to the stuff in between visits, so I could go in cold".<ref>DeRogatis (2003), p. 194</ref> The Lanois<U+2013>Eno team used [[lateral thinking]] and a philosophical approach<U+2014>popularised by Eno's [[Oblique Strategies]]<U+2014>that contrasted with ''Rattle and Hum'' producer [[Jimmy Iovine]]'s direct and retro style.<ref name="g44" />

===Berlin sessions===
The band believed that "domesticity [w]as the enemy of rock 'n' roll" and that to work on the album, they needed to remove themselves from their normal family-oriented routines. With a "[[New Europe]]" emerging at the end of the [[Cold War]], they chose Berlin, in the centre of the reuniting continent, as a source of inspiration for a more European musical aesthetic.<ref name="fricke" /><ref name="g43" /><ref name="Flanagan 1996, p. 7">Flanagan (1996), pp. 6<U+2013>7</ref> They recorded at [[Hansa Studios]] in [[West Berlin]], near the recently opened [[Berlin Wall]]. Several acclaimed records were made at Hansa, including two of [[David Bowie]]'s "[[Berlin Trilogy]]" with Eno, and [[Iggy Pop]]'s ''[[The Idiot (album)|The Idiot]]''.<ref name="m216" /> U2 arrived on 3 October 1990 on the last flight into [[East Berlin]] on the eve of [[German reunification]].<ref name="m216" /> Expecting to be inspired, they instead found Berlin to be depressing and gloomy.<ref name="m221">McCormick (2006), p. 221</ref> The collapse of the Berlin Wall had resulted in a state of malaise in Germany. The band found their East Berlin hotel to be dismal and the winter inhospitable, while the run-down condition of Hansa Studios and its location in an [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] ballroom added to the "bad vibe".<ref name="m221" /><ref name="prop-berlin">{{cite magazine |title=The Berlin Sessions |magazine=Propaganda |issue=14 |date=1991-06-01}}</ref>

[[File:Meistersaal leer.jpg|thumb|left|U2 initially recorded at Berlin's [[Hansa Studios]] in a former [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] ballroom.|alt=A ballroom with hardwood floors, and a ceiling decorated with chandeliers and octagon-shaped tiles. The wall on the left is decorated with dark wood panels, red walls, and windows. On the right is a small stage with a piano in front.]]
Morale worsened once the sessions commenced, as the band worked long days but could not agree on a musical direction.<ref name="prop-berlin" /> The Edge had been listening to electronic dance music and to [[industrial music|industrial]] bands like [[Einst<U+00FC>rzende Neubauten]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], the [[Young Gods]], and [[KMFDM]]. He and Bono advocated new musical directions along these lines. In contrast, Mullen was listening to [[classic rock]] acts such as [[Blind Faith]], [[Cream (band)|Cream]], and [[Jimi Hendrix]], and was learning how to "play around the beat".<ref name="fricke" /><ref name="m215" /> Along with Clayton, he was more comfortable with a sound similar to U2's previous work and was resistant to the proposed innovations.<ref name="fricke" /><ref name="m221" /> Further, The Edge's interest in dance club mixes and [[drum machine]]s made Mullen feel that his contributions as a drummer were being diminished.<ref name="m221" /> Lanois was expecting the "textural and emotional and cinematic U2" of ''The Unforgettable Fire'' and ''The Joshua Tree'', and he did not understand the "throwaway, trashy kinds of things" on which Bono and The Edge were working.<ref name="fricke" /> Compounding the divisions between the two camps was a change in the band's longstanding songwriting relationship; Bono and The Edge were working more closely together, writing material in isolation from the rest of the group.<ref name="m215" /><ref name="Flanagan 1996, p. 7"/><ref>Graham (1996), p. 28</ref>

{{Quote box
| quote = "At the instant we were recording it, I got a very strong sense of its power. We were all playing together in the big recording room, a huge, eerie ballroom full of ghosts of the war, and everything fell into place. It was a reassuring moment, when everyone finally went, 'oh great, this album has started.' It's the reason you're in a band<U+2014>when the spirit descends upon you and you create something truly affecting. 'One' is an incredibly moving piece. It hits straight into the heart."
| source = <U+2014>[[The Edge]], on the recording of "[[One (U2 song)|One]]"<ref name="one" />
| width = 27%
| align = right
| style = padding:10px;
}}

U2 found that they were neither prepared nor well-rehearsed, and that their ideas were not evolving into completed songs.<ref name="m221" /> For the first time, the group could not find consensus during their disagreements and felt that they were not making progress.<ref name="m221" /> Bono and Lanois, in particular, had an argument that almost came to blows during the writing of "Mysterious Ways".<ref>Stokes (1996), p. 104</ref> With a sense of going nowhere, the band considered breaking up.<ref name="flan10">Flanagan (1996), pp. 10<U+2013>11</ref> Eno visited for a few days, and understanding their attempts to deconstruct the band, he assured them that their progress was better than they thought.<ref name="flan10" /><ref name="stokes-one" /> By adding unusual effects and sounds, he showed that The Edge's pursuit for new sonic territory was not incompatible with Mullen's and Lanois' "desire to hold on to solid song structures".<ref name="flan10" /> In December, a breakthrough was achieved with the writing of the song "[[One (U2 song)|One]]".<ref name="one">McCormick (2006), pp. 221<U+2013>224</ref> The Edge combined two [[chord progression]]s on guitar, and finding inspiration, the group quickly improvised most of the song. It provided much-needed reassurance, and re-validated their longstanding "blank page approach" to writing and recording together.<ref name="one" /><ref>Flanagan (1996), pp. 11<U+2013>12</ref>

U2 returned to Dublin for Christmas, where they discussed their future together and all recommitted to the group. Listening to the tapes, they agreed their material sounded better than they originally thought.<ref>Flanagan (1996), p. 12</ref> They briefly returned to Berlin in January 1991 to finish their Hansa work.<ref name="mcg134-5">McGee (2008), pp. 134<U+2013>135</ref>  Although just two songs were delivered during their two months in Berlin, The Edge said that in retrospect, working there had been more productive and inspirational than the output had suggested.<ref name="one" /><ref name="stokes-one">Stokes (1996), p. 98</ref><ref name="adams" /> The band had been removed from a familiar environment, providing a certain "texture and cinematic location", and many of their incomplete ideas were to be revisited in the Dublin sessions with success.<ref name="one" />

===Dublin sessions===
[[File:Bono and Edge in Auckland.jpg|upright|thumb|Bono and The Edge, pictured in 2006, lived within walking distance of Elsinore, contributing to the more relaxed sessions there.|alt=Bono and The Edge stand on a red and black concert stage at a darkened venue with audience members behind them. Bono holds his right hand to his mouth, while The Edge holds a guitar and speaks into a microphone.]]
In February 1991, U2 resumed the album's sessions in the seaside manor "Elsinore" in [[Dalkey]], renting the house for <U+20A4>10,000 per month.<ref name="mcg134-5" /><ref name="adams">{{cite web |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1994_articles/mar94/u2robbieadams.html |title=U2 & Robbie Adams |work=[[Sound on Sound]] |first=Paul |last=Tingen |date=1994-03 |accessdate=2010-01-08}}</ref> Lanois' strategy to record in houses, mansions, or castles was something he believed brought atmosphere to the recordings.<ref name="adams" /> Dublin audio services company Big Bear Sound installed a recording studio in the house,<ref name="mcg134-5" /> with the recording room in a converted garage diagonally beneath the control room. Video cameras and TV monitors were used to monitor the spaces.<ref name="adams" /> Within walking distance of Bono and The Edge's homes, the sessions at Elsinore were more relaxed and productive.<ref name="mcg134-5" /><ref name="comp" /><ref name="stokes96">Stokes (1996), p. 96</ref> The band struggled with one particular song<U+2014>later released as the B-side "Lady With the Spinning Head"<U+2014>but three separate tracks, "[[The Fly (U2 song)|The Fly]]", "[[Ultraviolet (Light My Way)]]" and "[[Zoo Station]]" were derived from it.<ref name="McCormick 225">McCormick (2006), p. 225</ref> During the writing of "The Fly", Bono conceived an alternate persona based on a pair of oversized black sunglasses that he wore to lighten the mood in the studio.<ref name="mcg134-5" /><ref name="comp" /> Bono developed the character into a leather-clad egomaniac also called "The Fly", and he assumed this alter-ego for the band's subsequent public appearances and live performances on the [[Zoo TV Tour]].

In April, tapes from the earlier Berlin sessions were leaked and [[Bootleg recording|bootlegged]]. Bono dismissed the leaked demos as "gobbledygook", and The Edge likened the situation to "being violated".<ref name="details">{{cite magazine|title=U2 Anew|magazine=[[Details (magazine)|Details]]|first=Sean|last=O'Hagan|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|date=1992-09-01}}</ref> The leak shook the band's confidence and soured their collective mood a few weeks.<ref name="Q-int" /> Staffing logistics meant that the group found themselves with three engineers, and they decided to split recording between Elsinore and The Edge's home studio.<ref name="adams" /> Engineer Robbie Adams said the approach raised morale and activity levels: "There was always something different to listen to, always something exciting happening."<ref name="adams" /> To record all of the band's material and test different arrangements, the engineers utilised a technique they called "fatting", which allowed them to achieve more than 48 tracks of audio by using a 24-track [[analogue recording]], a [[Digital Audio Tape|DAT]] machine, and a synchroniser.<ref name="adams" /> At the end of May, final lyrics and vocal takes had yet to be completed, but Lanois believed some of the in-progress songs would become worldwide hits.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Lanois |magazine=Propaganda |issue=14 |date=1991-06-01}}</ref>

During the Dublin sessions, Eno was sent tapes of the previous two months' work, which he called a "total disaster". Joining U2 in the studio, he stripped away what he thought to be excessive [[overdubbing]]. The group believes his intervention saved the album.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.rocksbackpages.com/article.html?ArticleID=2327 |title=Brian Eno|first=Andy |last=Gill |magazine=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] |date=1995-06|accessdate=2010-06-12}} Note: A subscription is required to access the article.</ref> Eno theorised that the band was too close to their music, explaining, "if you know a piece of music terribly well and the mix changes and the bass guitar goes very quiet, you still hear the bass. You're so accustomed to it being there that you compensate and remake it in your mind."<ref name="eno-prop">{{cite magazine |title=Eno |magazine=Propaganda |issue=16 |date=1992-06-01}}</ref> Eno also assisted them through a crisis point one month before the deadline to finish recording; he recalls that "everything seemed like a mess", and he insisted the band take a two-week holiday from working on the album. The break gave them a clearer perspective and added decisiveness.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.rocksbackpages.com/article.html?ArticleID=8644 |title=Brian Eno: "So Why Are We Doing This?"|magazine=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] |first=Andy |last=Gill |date=2001-05|accessdate=2010-06-12}} Note: A subscription is required to access the article.</ref>

After work at Elsinore finished in July, Eno, Flood, Lanois, and previous U2 producer [[Steve Lillywhite]] [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] the tracks at [[Windmill Lane Studios]].<ref name="mcg134-5" /><ref name="g45">Graham (2004), p. 45</ref><ref name="f19">Flanagan (1996), p. 19</ref> Each producer created his own mixes of the songs, and the band either picked the version they preferred or requested that certain aspects of each be combined.<ref name="f19" /> Additional recording and mixing continued at a frenetic pace until the 21 September deadline,<ref>McGee (2008), p. 137</ref> including last-minute changes to "The Fly" and "One".<ref name="finish">McCormick (2006), p. 232</ref> The final night was spent devising a running order for the record. The following day, The Edge travelled to Los Angeles with the album's tapes for [[Audio mastering|mastering]].<ref name="finish" />

==Composition==
===Music===
{{Quote box
| quote = "We're at a point where production has gotten so slick that people don't trust it anymore. [...] We were starting to lose trust in the conventional sound of rock & roll <U+2014> the conventional sound of guitar [...] those big reverb-laden drum sounds of the '80s or those big, beautiful, pristine vocal sounds with all this lush ambience and reverb. So we found ourselves searching for other sounds that had more life and more freshness."
| source = <U+2014>The Edge, explaining the band's motivation for seeking a new sound<ref>{{cite magazine |title=U2's Zoo World Order |first=Anthony |last=DeCurtis |authorlink=Anthony DeCurtis |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=1993-10-14|issue=667}}</ref>
| width = 29%
| align = right
| style = padding:10px;
}}

U2 is credited with composing the music for all of ''Achtung Baby''{{'}}s tracks,<ref name="album" /> despite periods of separated songwriting. The band wrote much of the music through [[jam sessions]], a common practice for them.<ref name="m221" /> The record is a mix of anthemic tracks similar to the group's previous work and darker songs that explore new sonic territory for the group.<ref name="hotpress" /> They referred to the album's musical departure as "the sound of four men chopping down The Joshua Tree".<ref name="chop-joshua">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/music/u2/reviews/10793 |title=U2 <U+2013> The Joshua Tree Re-Mastered (R1987) |magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |first=Andrew |last=Mueller|authorlink=Andrew Mueller |accessdate=2009-12-31}}</ref><ref name="ach-stations" /> Accordingly, the distorted [[introduction (music)|introduction]] to the opening track "[[Zoo Station]]" was intended to make listeners think the record was broken or was mistakenly not the new U2 album.<ref name="comp" /> Author Susan Fast said that with the group's use of technology in the song's opening, "there can be no mistake that U2 has embraced sound resources new to them".<ref name="exp">Fast (2000), pp. 45<U+2013>48</ref> 

For the album, The Edge often eschewed his normally minimalistic approach to guitar playing and his trademark chiming, echo-heavy sound in favour of a style that incorporated more [[guitar solo|solos]], [[Consonance and dissonance|dissonance]], and [[audio feedback|feedback]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Achtung Baby|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|first=Chris|last=Snider|date=1991-11-29}}</ref> Industrial influences and guitar effects<U+2014>particularly [[distortion (music)|distortion]]<U+2014>contribute to a "metallic" style and "harder textures".<ref name="rs">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/reviews/album/7076/36762|title=Review: Achtung Baby|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Elysa|last=Gardner|date=1992-01-09|issue=621|accessdate=2010-04-26}}</ref><ref name="orlsent" /><ref name="globe" /> Music journalist Bill Wyman said The Edge's guitar playing on the closing track "[[Love is Blindness]]" sounded like a "dentist's drill".<ref name="ew" /> The Edge's experimenting with various [[Effects unit|effects pedals]] led to breakthroughs in the writing of "[[Even Better Than the Real Thing]]" and "[[Mysterious Ways (song)|Mysterious Ways]]".<ref name="comp" />

On the group's previous work, Bono's vocals were centre-stage in melody and mix, whereas on ''Achtung Baby'', they are often lower in the mix or in a lower [[vocal register|register]].<ref name="orlsent">{{cite news |title=Achtung Baby |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |first=Patty |last=Gettelman |date=1991-11-06}}</ref><ref name="hotpress">{{cite magazine |title=Review: Achtung Baby |magazine=[[Hot Press]] |first=Niall |last=Stokes|authorlink=Niall Stokes|date=1991-11-13}}</ref> On many tracks<U+2014>such as "[[The Fly (U2 song)|The Fly]]" and "Zoo Station"<U+2014>Bono sang as a character,<ref name="g44">Graham (2004), p. 44</ref> and his vocals were treated with [[Audio signal processing|processing]].<ref name="globe" /><ref name="ew" /><ref name="nyt" /> This was done to give his voice a different emotional feel and distinguish it from his past vocals.<ref name="stokes96" />

The rhythm section is more pronounced in the mix on ''Achtung Baby'',<ref name="g44"/>  and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]-inspired electronic dance beats are featured on half the album's tracks, most prominently "The Fly".<ref name="rs" />  Elysa Gardner of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' compared the layering of dance beats into guitar-heavy mixes to songs by British bands [[Happy Mondays]] and [[Jesus Jones]].<ref name="rs" /> "Mysterious Ways" combines a funky guitar riff with a danceable, [[conga]]-laden beat,<ref name="austin">{{cite web |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/review?oid=oid%3A81288 |title=Review <U+2013> U2: Achtung Baby |work=[[Austin Chronicle]] |first=Christopher |last=Gray |date=2001-03-30 |accessdate=2009-10-13}}</ref> for what Bono calls "U2 at our funkiest...&nbsp;[[Sly and The Family Stone]] meets Madchester [[baggy]]."<ref name="comp" /> Amidst layers of distorted guitars, "The Fly" and "Zoo Station" feature industrial-influenced percussion<ref name="Stokes 1996, p. 95"/><ref>Graham (2004), p. 47</ref><ref name="Stokes 1996, p. 102">Stokes (1996), p. 102</ref><U+2014>the [[timbre]] of Mullen's drums exhibits a "cold, processed sound, something like beating on a tin can", according to author Albin Zak.<ref>Zak (2001), pp. 68<U+2013>70</ref>

===Lyrics===
{{Listen
| filename = U2 Zoo Station.ogg
| title = "Zoo Station"
| description = The introduction to "[[Zoo Station]]" was meant to make listeners think "This record is broken" or "This can't be the new U2 record".<ref name="comp" />
| filename2 = U2 One.ogg	
| title2 = "One"	
| description2 = The Edge composed the riff to "[[One (U2 song)|One]]" by combining two chord progressions he was working on, leading to the song's improvised writing. The lyrics reflect a bitter conversation between two people.
| filename3 = Fly sample.ogg
| title3 = "The Fly"
| description3 = "[[The Fly (U2 song)|The Fly]]" was chosen as the first single because its dance beats, distorted vocals, and hard industrial edge sounded nothing like typical U2.<ref name="Stokes 1996, p. 102"/><ref name="g49">Graham (2004), p. 49</ref><ref>Flanagan (1996), p. 31</ref>
}}
Bono is credited as the sole lyricist.<ref name="album" /> In contrast to their previous work, U2 avoided political and social statements on ''Achtung Baby''. Instead, the album is more personal and introspective, examining love, sexuality, spirituality, faith, and betrayal.<ref name="g46">Graham (2004), p. 46</ref><ref>Stokes (1996), p. 100</ref><ref>Flanagan (1996), p. 82</ref> The lyrics, darker in tone, examine troubled personal relationships and exude feelings of confusion, loneliness, and inadequacy.<ref name="rs" /><ref name="dlp139">de la Parra (1994), p. 139</ref><ref name="latimes">{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/61547027.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Nov+17%2C+1991&author=ROBERT+HILBURN&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=58&desc=U2%27s+Daring+Descent+Into+Darkness|title=U2's Daring Descent Into Darkness|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Robert |last=Hilburn|authorlink=Robert Hilburn|date=1991-11-17|accessdate=2009-12-31}} Note: A subscription is required to access the article.</ref> Central to these themes was The Edge's separation from his wife and mother of his three children, which occurred halfway through the album's recording. The pain focused him on the record and led him to advocate more personal themes, and it also influenced Bono's lyrical contributions.<ref name="fricke" /><ref name="m221" /><ref>Flanagan (1996), pp. 14<U+2013>15</ref><ref>Assayas (2005), pp. 64<U+2013>66</ref> Bono found inspiration from his own personal life, citing the births of his two daughters in 1989 and 1991 as major influences.<ref name="m216" />

Of the album's personal nature, Bono said that there were a lot of "blood and guts" in the record.<ref name="ach-stations" /> His  lyrics to the ballad "[[One (U2 song)|One]]" were inspired by the band members' struggling relationships and the German reunification.<ref name="legends">{{cite episode|title=U2|series=[[VH1's Legends|Legends]]|network=[[VH1]]|season=1|number=6|airdate=1998-12-11|quote=Maybe it summed up the way we felt as a band, trying to kind of go somewhere, but not being able to at the time.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Beyonce, U2 draw fans at MTV Europe Music Awards | url = http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2009-11-05-MTV-europe-music-awards_N.htm | newspaper = [[USA Today]] | author = [[Associated Press]] | date = 2009-11-05|accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref> The Edge described the song as, on one level, a "bitter, twisted, vitriolic conversation between two people who've been through some nasty, heavy stuff".<ref name="one" /> Similarly, "[[Ultraviolet (Light My Way)]]" describes a strained relationship and unease over obligations,<ref name="g50">Graham (2004), p. 50</ref> and on "[[Acrobat (song)|Acrobat]]", Bono sings about weakness, hypocrisy, and inadequacy.<ref name="Stokes 108">Stokes (1996), p. 108</ref> The [[torch songs]] of [[Roy Orbison]], [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]], and [[Jacques Brel]] were major influences, demonstrated on tracks such as "[[Who's Gonna Ride Your Wild Horses]]" (describing an argument between a couple), "[[So Cruel]]" (about unrequited love, jealousy, obsession, and possessiveness),<ref name="g49" /> and the closing track, "Love Is Blindness" (a bleak description of failing love).<ref name="g45" /><ref name="Stokes 108" /><ref name="q"/>

U2 biographer [[Bill Flanagan]] credits Bono's habit of keeping his lyrics "in flux until the last minute" with providing a narrative coherence to the album.<ref name="flan20">Flanagan (1996), p. 20</ref> Flanagan interpreted ''Achtung Baby'' as using the moon as a metaphor for a dark woman seducing the singer away from his virtuous love, the sun; he is tempted away from domestic life by an exciting nightlife and tests how far he can go before returning home.<ref>Flanagan (1996), p. 187</ref> For Flanagan, "[[Tryin' to Throw Your Arms Around the World]]" on the album's latter third describes the character stumbling home in a drunken state, and the final three songs<U+2014>"Ultraviolet" (Light My Way), "Acrobat", and "Love Is Blindness"<U+2014>are about how the couple deal with the suffering they have forced on each other.<ref name="flan20" />

Despite the record's darker themes, many lyrics are more flippant and sexual than those from the band's previous work.<ref name="hotpress" /><ref name="rs-fly">{{cite magazine |title=Bono: The Rolling Stone Interview |first=Alan |last=Light |authorlink=Alan Light |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1993-03-04|issue=651}}</ref> This reflects the group's revisiting some of the [[Dadaist]] characters and stage antics they dabbled with in the late 1970s as teenagers but abandoned for more literal themes in the 1980s.<ref name="Stokes 1996, p. 95">Stokes (1996), p. 95</ref> While the band had previously been opposed to [[materialism]], they examined and flirted with this value on the album and the Zoo TV Tour.<ref name="g46" /> The title and lyrics of "[[Even Better Than the Real Thing]]" are "reflective of the times [the band] were living in, when people were no longer looking for the truth, [they] were all looking for instant gratification".<ref name="comp" /> "Trashy" and "throwaway" were among the band's buzzwords for the record, leading to many tracks in this vein. The chorus of "Ultraviolet (Light My Way)" features the pop lyrical clich<U+00E9> "baby, baby, baby",<ref>Stokes (1996), pp. 106<U+2013>107</ref> juxtaposed against the dark lyrics in the verses.<ref name="g50" /> Bono wrote the lyrics to "The Fly" as the song's eponymous character by composing a sequence of "single-line aphorisms".<ref name="Stokes 1996, p. 102" /> He called the song "like a crank call from Hell...&nbsp; but [the caller] likes it there".<ref name="comp">McCormick (2006), pp. 224<U+2013>225, 227, 232</ref> 

Religious imagery is present throughout the record. "[[Until the End of the World (song)|Until the End of the World]]" is an imagined conversation between [[Jesus Christ]] and his betrayer, [[Judas Iscariot]].<ref name="comp" /> On "Acrobat", Bono sings about feelings of spiritual alienation in the line "I'd [[Eucharist|break bread and wine]] / If there was a church I could receive in".<ref>{{cite magazine |title=U2's Mysterious Ways |magazine=Sides |author=Bowden, Tony, and Jennifer Stewart |date=1994-07-01}}</ref> In many tracks, Bono's lyrics about women carry religious connotations, describing them as spirits, life or light,<ref>Gilmour (2005), pp. 66, 76</ref> and idols to be worshipped.<ref>Stein (1999), pp. 269<U+2013>272</ref> Religious interpretations of the album are the subject of the book ''Meditations on Love in the Shadow of the Fall''.<ref>Catanzarite (2007), pp. 1<U+2013>3</ref>
{{Clear}}

==Packaging and title==
{{Quote box	
| quote = "[...] the very title ''Achtung Baby'' strives for lack of significance and <U+2014> just as insignificantly <U+2014> the sleeve itself is not the usual single cinematic image of heroic import but rather a grid of snapshots evoking, if a little cleanly, the slapdash glory that was [[Robert Frank]]'s artwork for the [[The Rolling Stones|<nowiki>[</nowiki>Rolling<nowiki>]</nowiki> Stones]]' ''[[Exile on Main Street]]''."
| source = <U+2014>Mat Snow, contrasting ''Achtung Baby'' with U2's previous albums<ref name="q" />
| width = 25%
| align = right
| style = padding:10px;
}}
The sleeve artwork for ''Achtung Baby'' was designed by Steve Averill, who had created the majority of U2's album covers.<ref name="prop-cover">{{cite magazine |title=(<U+0102>hk-t<U+014F><U+014F>ng B<U+0101>y-bi) Covered |magazine=Propaganda |issue=15 |date=1991-12-01}}</ref> To mirror their change in musical direction, the band considered sleeve concepts that used multiple colour images to contrast with the seriousness of the mostly black-and-white images of their previous album sleeves.<ref name="prop-cover" /><ref name="mcg138">McGee (2008), p. 138</ref> Rough sketches and designs were created early during the recording sessions, and some more experimental designs were conceived to closely resemble, as Averill put it, "dance-music oriented sleeves. We just did them to show how extreme we could go and then everyone came back to levels that they were happy with. But if we hadn't gone to these extremes it may not have the been the cover it is now."<ref name="prop-cover" />

An initial photo shoot with the band's long-time photographer, [[Anton Corbijn]], was done near U2's Berlin hotel in late 1990.<ref>McGee (2008), p. 133</ref> Most of the photos were black-and-white,<ref name="prop-cover" /> and the group felt they were not indicative of the spirit of the new album. They re-commissioned Corbijn for an additional two-week photo shoot in [[Tenerife]] in February 1991,<ref name="mcg134-5" /> for which they dressed up and mingled with the crowds of the annual [[Carnival of Santa Cruz de Tenerife]], presenting a more playful side of themselves.<ref name="mcg134-5" /> It was during the group's time in Tenerife, and during a four-day shoot in [[Morocco]] in July, that they were photographed in [[drag (clothing)|drag]].<ref name="mcg134-5" /> Additional photos were taken in Dublin in June, including a shot of a naked Clayton.<ref>McGee (2008), p. 136</ref> The images were intended to confound expectations of U2,<ref name="finish" /> and their full colour contrasted with the monochrome imagery on past sleeves.<ref name="mcg138" />

[[Image:Rockhall lobby cars 2005.jpg|thumb|upright|left|alt=Three cars hang from the ceiling of a building in front of a windowed wall. The car in the foreground has an orange leopard-skin pattern on the exterior, and it is hanging upside down, facing upwards. Two cars hang in the background facing downwards; the one on the left, facing left, is painted peach with sticks embedded in the exterior; the one on the right, facing right, is painted white with small black words.|[[Trabant]]s from the Zoo TV Tour, displayed at the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]. The group were photographed with several elaborately painted Trabants for the album sleeve.]]
A single image scheme had been planned for the sleeve, and among the photographs considered were those of a cow on an Irish farm in [[County Kildare]], the nude Clayton, and the band driving a [[Trabant]]<U+2014>an East German automobile they became fond of as a symbol for a changing Europe.<ref name="prop-cover" /> Ultimately, a multiple image scheme was used, as U2, Corbijn, Averill, and the producers could not agree on a single image;<ref name="prop-cover" /> the resulting front sleeve is a 4<U+00D7>4 squared montage.<ref name="finish" /> The band wanted to balance the "colder European feel of the mainly black-and-white Berlin images with the much warmer exotic climates of Santa Cruz and Morocco".<ref name="prop-cover" /> Some photographs were used because they were striking on their own, while others were used because of their ambiguity.<ref name="prop-cover" /> Images of the band with Trabants, several of which were painted bright colours, appear on the sleeve and throughout the album booklet. These vehicles were later incorporated into the Zoo TV Tour set as part of the lighting system.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Zoo TV Station Talent |magazine=Propaganda |date=1992-06-01 |issue=16}}</ref><ref>"Trabantland." {{cite video |title=[[Zoo TV: Live from Sydney]] |publisher=[[Island Records|Island]] / [[Universal Music Group|UMG]] |location=Special Edition |medium=DVD |date=2006}}</ref> The nude photo of Clayton was placed on the rear cover of the record. On the US [[compact disc]] and [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] sleeves, Clayton's penis is censored with a black "X" or a [[four-leaf clover]],<ref name="backgrounder">{{cite web |url=http://www.u2.com/discography/index/album/albumId/4009/tagName/studio_albums |title=Achtung Baby |work=U2.com|publisher=[[Live Nation]]|accessdate=2009-08-31}}</ref> while [[vinyl record|vinyl]] editions feature the photo uncensored.<ref name="mcg138" /> In 2003, music television network [[VH1]] ranked ''Achtung Baby''{{'}}s sleeve at number 39 on its list of the "50 Greatest Album Covers".<ref>{{cite episode|title=50 Greatest Album Covers|series=[[The Greatest (TV series)|The Greatest]]|network=[[VH1]]|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=67956|number=088|airdate=2003-09-20}}</ref> Three years later, Bono called the sleeve his favourite U2 cover artwork.<ref name="m234">McCormick (2006), p. 234</ref>

The album's title, "Achtung Baby", is German for "Attention, baby!" or "Watch out, baby!", and it was used by the band's sound engineer Joe O'Herlihy during recording.<ref name="g43" /> He reportedly took the phrase from the [[Mel Brooks]] film ''[[The Producers (1968 film)|The Producers]]''.<ref name="finish" /> The title was selected in August 1991 near the end of the album sessions.<ref name="prop-cover" /> According to Bono, it was an ideal title, as it was attention-grabbing, referenced Germany, and hinted at either romance or birth, both of which were themes on the album.<ref name="finish" /> The band was determined not to highlight the seriousness of the lyrics and instead sought to "erect a mask", a concept that was further developed on the Zoo TV Tour, particularly through characters such as "The Fly".<ref name="Flanagan 1996, p. 21">Flanagan (1996), pp. 21<U+2013>22</ref> Of the title, Bono said in 1992, "It's a con, in a way. We call it ''Achtung Baby'', grinning up our sleeves in all the photography. But it's probably the heaviest record we've ever made. [...] It tells you a lot about packaging, because the press would have killed us if we'd called it anything else."<ref name="fricke" />

For the album, U2 had considered several titles, including ''Man''<U+2014>in contrast to the group's debut, ''[[Boy (album)|Boy]]''<ref name="rockbig">{{cite magazine |title=Rock and Roll Should Be This Big! |magazine=[[NME]] |first=Stuart |last=Bailie |date=1992-06-13}}</ref><U+2014>''69'', ''Zoo Station'', and ''Adam'', which would have been paired with the nude photo of Clayton.<ref name="fricke" /><ref name="prop-cover" /> Other possible titles included ''Fear of Women'', and ''Cruise Down Main Street''<U+2014>in reference to [[The Rolling Stones]]' record ''[[Exile on Main St.]]'' and the cruise missiles launched on [[Baghdad]] during the [[Gulf War]].<ref name="Flanagan 1996, p. 21"/> Most of the proposed titles were rejected out of the belief that people would see them as pretentious and "another Big Statement from U2".<ref name="rockbig" /> The album's lighthearted title influenced other musicians, including [[David Bowie]], who was an inspiration to U2 and Eno during recording of ''Achtung Baby''. Bowie's band [[Tin Machine]] called their live record ''[[Tin Machine Live: Oy Vey, Baby]]'', putting a Yiddish spin on U2's German title.<ref>Perone (2007), p. 105</ref>

==Release==
As early as December 1990, the music press reported that U2 would be recording a dance-oriented album and that it would be released in the summer 1991.<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318875,00.html | title = U2 Can Dance | magazine = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | issue = 45 | first = Elysa | last = Gardner | date = 1990-12-21 | accessdate = 2009-12-31}}</ref> In August 1991, [[sound collage]] artists [[Negativland]] released an [[Extended play|EP]] entitled ''[[U2 (EP)|U2]]'' that parodied U2's song "[[I Still Haven't Found What I'm Looking For]]" and used the band's likenesses on the cover. [[Island Records]] objected to the cover, believing consumers would confuse the EP for U2's new record. Island successfully sued for copyright infringement but were criticised in the music press, as were U2, although they were not involved in the litigation.<ref name="ach-stations">{{cite magazine |title=Achtung Stations |magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |first=Stephen |last=Dalton |date=2004-10-26}}</ref><ref name="negativland">{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-08/entertainment/ca-32858_1_pop-music |title=Positively Outspoken Negativland |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Rick |last=Vanderknyff |date=1993-05-08 |accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref> ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''{{'}}s Stephen Dalton believes that much of the negative headlines were tempered by the success of ''Achtung Baby''{{'}}s first single, "The Fly".<ref name="ach-stations" /> Sounding nothing like U2's typical style, it was selected as the lead single to announce the group's new musical direction.<ref name="comp" /> It was released on 21 October 1991, a month before the album, and it topped the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming the group's second number-one single in the UK.<ref name="uk40" />

Island Records and U2 refused to make advance copies of the album available to the press until just a few days before the release date, preferring fans to listen to the record before reading reviews. The decision came amid rumours of tensions within the band, and David Browne compared it to the Hollywood practice of withholding review copies of films from the media before release whenever they receive poor word-of-mouth press.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,316187,00.html |issue=92 |title=U2 Would Worry|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=David |last=Browne |authorlink=David Browne |date=1991-11-15 |accessdate=2009-08-14}}</ref> ''Achtung Baby'' was released on 19 November 1991 on compact disc, tape cassette, and vinyl record. The album was the first release by a major act to use two so-called "[[eco-friendly]]" packages<U+2014>the cardboard [[Digipak]], and the [[jewel case]] without the long cardboard attachment.<ref name="backgrounder" /> The album was U2's first in three years and their first comprising entirely new material in over four years.<ref name="xxv"/> The group maintained a low profile after ''Achtung Baby''{{'}}s release, avoiding interviews and allowing critics and the public to make their own assessments.<ref name="g43" /> Instead of participating in an article with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine, U2 asked Eno to write one for them.<ref name="mcg134-5" />

"Mysterious Ways" was released as the second single five days after the release of ''Achtung Baby''. On the US [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]], the song topped the [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] and [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Album Rock Tracks]] charts and reached number nine on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]].<ref name="billboard-singles">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:gifwxqr5ldde~T51 |title=U2: Charts & Awards: Billboard Singles |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=2009-12-14}}</ref> The album also charted and sold well; in the US, ''Achtung Baby'' debuted at the top of the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] on 7 December 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/billboard-200?chartDate=1991-12-07|title=Music Albums, Top 200 Albums & Music Album Charts <U+2013> Week of December 07, 1991|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]]|accessdate=2010-04-21}}</ref> It fell to number three the following week,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/billboard-200?chartDate=1991-12-14|title=Music Albums, Top 200 Albums & Music Album Charts <U+2013> Week of December 14, 1991|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]]|accessdate=2010-04-21}}</ref> but spent its first 13 weeks on the chart within the top ten.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/billboard-200?chartDate=1992-03-07|title=Music Albums, Top 200 Albums & Music Album Charts <U+2013> Week of March 07, 1992|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media, Inc]]|accessdate=2010-04-21}}</ref> In total, it spent 97 weeks on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name="billboard-album" /> The album sold 295,000 copies in the US in its first week,<ref name="negativland" /> and on 21 January 1992, the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] [[RIAA certification|certified]] it platinum.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=U2: It's a Business |magazine=[[Hit Parader]] |first=Bob |last=Grossweiner|publisher=[[Charlton Publications]] |date=1992-06-01}}</ref> ''Achtung Baby'' peaked at number two on the [[UK Albums Chart]],<ref name="ukalbum" /> while topping the [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' 100]] in Canada,<ref name="rpm-album" /> the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] in Australia, and the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|RIANZ Top 40 Albums]] in New Zealand.<ref name="australia" /> The record sold seven&nbsp;million copies in its first three months on sale.<ref name="dlp139"/>

Three additional singles were released in 1992. "One", released in March to coincide with the beginning of the Zoo TV Tour, reached number seven in the UK and number ten in the US charts,<ref name="uk40" /> and like its predecessor, topped both the Album Rock and Modern Rock Tracks charts.<ref name="billboard-singles" /> The song has since become regarded as one of the greatest of all time, ranking highly on many critics' lists.<ref name="one-greatest-record">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3281327.stm |title=U2's One named 'greatest record' |publisher=[[BBC Online]] |date=2003-11-18 |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> The fourth single from ''Achtung Baby'', "Even Better Than the Real Thing", was released in June. The album version of the song peaked at number 12 on the UK Singles Chart,<ref name="uk40" /> while becoming the third single from ''Achtung Baby'' to top the Album Rock Tracks chart.<ref name="billboard-singles" /> A remix version of the song peaked at number eight in the UK.<ref name="uk40" /> "Who's Gonna Ride Your Wild Horses" followed as the fifth and final single in August 1992. It peaked at number 14 on the UK Singles Chart,<ref name="uk40" /> and number two on the US Album Rock Tracks chart.<ref name="billboard-singles" /> All five singles charted within the top 20 in Ireland,<ref name="Irish S" /> Australia,<ref name="australia" /> Canada,<ref name="rpm-single" /> and UK.<ref name="uk40" /> By the end of 1992, ''Achtung Baby'' had sold 10&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref>Flanagan (1996), p. 133</ref>

In May 1992, U2 released ''Achtung Baby: The Videos, The Cameos, and a Whole Lot of Interference from Zoo TV'', a [[VHS]] compilation of nine [[music video]]s from the album. Running for 62 minutes, it was produced by Ned O'Hanlon and released by Island/[[Polygram]]. It included three music videos each for "One" and "Even Better than the Real Thing", along with videos for "The Fly", "Mysterious Ways", and "Until the End of the World".<ref name="prop-tour" /> Interspersed between the videos were clips of so-called "interference", comprising documentary footage, media clips, and other video footage similar to what was displayed at Zoo TV Tour concerts.<ref name="prop-tour" /> The release received a Gold certification in Canada.<ref name="Canada 2">{{cite web |url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php?page=2&wclause=WHERE+artist_name+like+%27%25U2%25%27+ORDER+BY+cert_date%2C+cert_award+&rcnt=81&csearch=40&nextprev=1 |title=CRIA Certification Results: U2 |publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] |date=1992-12-01 |accessdate=2009-11-17}}</ref>

==Reception==
{{Album ratings
|
|rev1    = [[Allmusic]]
|rev1Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name="allmusic" />
|rev2    = ''[[Austin Chronicle]]''
|rev2Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name="austin" />
|rev3    = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''
|rev3Score = {{rating|3|4}}<ref name="chitrib">{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-u2november91,0,2879134.story |title=U2 Loosens Up |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |first=Greg |last=Kot |authorlink=Greg Kot |date=1991-11-17|accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref>
|rev4    = [[Robert Christgau]]
|rev4Score = {{Rating-Christgau|dud}}<ref name="RobC" />
|rev5    = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''
|rev5Score = (A)<ref name="ew" />
|rev6    = ''[[Hot Press]]''
|rev6Score = (10/12)<ref name="hotpress" />
