|rev8Score = {{rating|4|4}}<ref name="orlsent" />
|rev9    = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''
|rev9Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name="q" />
|rev10    = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''
|rev10Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name="rs" />
}}

Upon its release, ''Achtung Baby'' received very favourable reviews from critics.<ref name="g43" /><ref name="details" /> Elysa Gardner of ''Rolling Stone'', in a four-and-a-half-star review, said that U2 had "proven that the same penchant for epic musical and verbal gestures that leads many artists to self-parody can, in more inspired hands, fuel the unforgettable fire that defines great rock & roll."<ref name="rs" /> The review said that the album, like its predecessor ''Rattle and Hum'', was an attempt by the band to "broaden its musical palette, but this time its ambitions are realized".<ref name="rs" /> [[David Browne]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the record an "A" and called it a "pristinely produced and surprisingly unpretentious return by one of the most impressive bands in the world".<ref name="ew">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,316330,00.html |title=Music Review: Achtung Baby |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |issue=94 |first=Bill |last=Wyman |date=1991-11-19 |accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref> Steve Morse of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' echoed these sentiments, stating that the album "not only reinvigorates their sound, but drops any self-righteousness. The songs focus on personal relationships, not on saving the world."<ref name="globe">{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/packages/U2Fleetcenter/album_review_achtung_baby |title=U2 bounces back |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |first=Steve |last=Morse |date=1991-11-15 |accessdate=2009-10-13 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5mRKSV7dN |archivedate=2009-12-31}}</ref> Morse commended the album's sonics, stating, "Clanging, knob-twisting sound effects run through the record, as does the metallic, head-snapping guitar of David (The Edge) Evans, who has never shone this brilliantly."<ref name="globe" /> In a five-star review, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' called ''Achtung Baby'' U2's "heaviest album to date. And best." The review praised the band and its production team for making "music of drama, depth, intensity and, believe it, funkiness".<ref name="q">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.rocksbackpages.com/article.html?ArticleID=10465 |title=U2: Achtung Baby |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |first=Mat |last=Snow |date=1991-12|issue=63 |accessdate=2009-08-14}}</ref> [[Jon Pareles]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' lauded the record not only for featuring "noisy, vertiginous arrangements, mostly layers of guitar", but also for the group's ability to "maintain its pop skills". The review concluded, "Stripped-down and defying its old formulas, U2 has given itself a fighting chance for the 1990s."<ref name="nyt">{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/1991/11/17/arts/recordings-view-u2-takes-a-turn-from-the-universal-to-the-domestic.html?scp=2 |title=U2 Takes a Turn From the Universal To the Domestic |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |first=Jon |last=Pareles |authorlink=Jon Pareles |date=1991-11-17 |accessdate=2009-10-13 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5mRKfqqvs |archivedate=2009-12-31}}</ref>

''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine featured a very positive review of ''Achtung Baby'', calling it a record of "major-league guitar crunching and mysterious, spacy chords" and "songs of love, temptation, loose political parable and tight personal confession". The review declared that U2 had successfully reinvented themselves.<ref name="time">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,974333,00.html |title=Dashing and Demanding |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=Jay|last=Cocks|authorlink=Jay Cocks|date=1991-11-25 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> In a four-star review, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' stated, "the arty, guitar-driven textures are among the band's most confident and vigorous ever". The newspaper said that despite the "exhilarating and sensual textures", the album is a difficult one for listeners because of the dark, introspective nature of the songs. The reviewer explained that U2 had lost some of its individuality by transitioning from inspirational songs in the past to tracks with more dismal subject matter, an area in popular music that was well-covered.<ref name="latimes" /> In a retrospective review, [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[Allmusic]] gave ''Achtung Baby'' a maximum score of five stars, praising the band's musical transformation as "thorough", "effective", and "endlessly inventive". Erlewine concluded that few artists at that stage in their career could have "recorded an album as adventurous or fulfilled their ambitions quite as successfully as U2 [did]".<ref name="allmusic">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:br61mpe39f2o |title=Achtung Baby <U+2013> Overview |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=2009-10-13}}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' was more critical of the record, calling it an "ambitious failure"; the review welcomed the experimentation but judged that when the group "strays from familiar territory, the results are hit-and-miss".<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Platter Du Jour |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |first=Jim |last=Greer|date=1991-12|issue=7|volume=9}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] rated it a dud, reflecting in his review of the group's 1993 album ''[[Zooropa]]'', "After many, many tries, ''Achtung Baby'' still sounded like a damnably diffuse U2 album to me, and I put it in the hall unable to describe a single song."<ref name="RobC">{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=u2 |title=U2 <U+2013> Consumer Guide Reviews |publisher=[[Robert Christgau]] |accessdate=2009-10-13}}</ref> In an otherwise positive retrospective, long-time U2 supporter Bill Graham said that the album seemed "over-calculated" in parts and that they were trying too hard to satisfy their critics.<ref name="g46" />

The success of ''Achtung Baby'' and the Zoo TV Tour re-established U2 as one of the most popular and critically acclaimed musical acts in the world. The group nearly swept ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s 1992 end-of-year readers' polls, winning honours for "Best Single" ("One"), "Artist of the Year", "Best Album", "Best Songwriter" (Bono), "Best Album Cover", and "Comeback of the Year", among others.<ref>McGee (2008), p. 159</ref> At the [[35th Grammy Awards]] in 1993, ''Achtung Baby'' won a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]], and it earned Lanois and Eno the award for [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year|Producer of the Year]]. The record was also nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] award.<ref name="backgrounder" />

==Zoo TV Tour==
[[File:ZooTVBstage.jpg|thumb|alt=In an outdoor stadium at night with an elaborate concert stage set bearing a logo that reads "Zoo TV", a number of white lights shine from various angles into the center of the audience on the stadium floor, where a musical performance is taking place on a very small stage.|The Zoo TV Tour was a multimedia-intensive event, featuring a stage that used dozens of video screens.<ref name="prop-tour" />]]

Following the release of ''Achtung Baby'', U2 staged a worldwide tour, titled the [[Zoo TV Tour]]. Like ''Achtung Baby'', the tour was an unequivocal break with the band's past. In contrast to the austere stage setups of previous U2 tours, Zoo TV was an elaborate multimedia event. It satirised television and the viewing public's over-stimulation by attempting to instill "sensory overload" in its audience.<ref name="ach-stations" /><ref name="closer-to-edge">{{cite magazine|title=Closer to the Edge|first=Olaf|last=Tyaransen|authorlink=Olaf Tyaransen|magazine=[[Hot Press]] |date=2002-12-04}}</ref><ref name="zooropa" /> The stage featured large video screens that showed visual effects, random video clips from [[pop culture]], and flashing text phrases. Live satellite link-ups, [[channel surfing]], [[crank call]]s, and video [[confessional]]s were incorporated into the shows.<ref name="prop-tour">{{cite magazine |title=Sixty-Nine Things You May Not Have Known About Life in the Zoo |magazine=Propaganda |issue=17 |date=1993-01-01}}</ref>

Whereas the group was known for its earnest performances in the 1980s, their Zoo TV performances were intentionally ironic and self-mocking.<ref name="ach-stations" /> Bono performed in-character as several personas he had conceived, including "The Fly", "Mirror Ball Man", and "Mr. MacPhisto". The majority of the album's songs were played at each show, and the [[set list]]s began with up to eight ''Achtung Baby'' songs in a row as a further sign that they were no longer the U2 of the 1980s.<ref name="mcg143">McGee (2008), p. 143</ref>

The tour began in February 1992 and comprised 157 shows over almost two years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.u2.com/tour/index/tour/id/54 |title=The Zoo TV Tour |work=U2.com|publisher=[[Live Nation]]|accessdate=2009-12-31}}</ref> During a six-month break, the band recorded the album ''[[Zooropa]]'', which was released in July 1993. It was inspired by Zoo TV and expanded on its themes of media oversaturation.<ref name="zooropa" /> By the time the tour concluded in December 1993, U2 had played to approximately 5.3&nbsp;million fans.<ref>Cogan (2008), p. 154</ref> In 2002, ''Q'' magazine said the Zoo TV Tour was "still the most spectacular rock tour staged by any band".<ref name="Q-int">{{cite magazine |title=10 Years of Turmoil Inside U2 |first=Tom |last=Doyle |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |date=2002-11|issue=196}}</ref>

{{Clear}}

==Legacy==
''Achtung Baby'' is certified 8<U+00D7> Platinum in the US by the RIAA,<ref name="ussales" /> and according to [[Nielsen Soundscan]], the album has sold 5.5&nbsp;million copies in the country, as of March 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE52B09F20090312 | title = FACTBOX: New U2 album is No. 1 in 30 countries | work = [[Reuters]] | date = 2009-03-12 | accessdate = 2010-05-07}}</ref> The record has been certified as 5<U+00D7> Platinum in Australia,<ref name="aussiecert" /> 4<U+00D7> Platinum in the UK,<ref name="ukcert" /> and Diamond in Canada, the highest certification award.<ref name="canadacert" /> Overall, 18&nbsp;million copies have been sold worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.reviewonline.com/page/content.detail/id/518682.html |title=Lincoln Park director to speak at U2 conference |newspaper=The Review |first=Jen |last=Matsick |date=2009-09-13 |accessdate=2009-12-31 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5mRJkKtH9 |archivedate=2009-12-31}}</ref> It is the group's second-highest-selling record after ''The Joshua Tree'', which has sold 25&nbsp;million copies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article5840868.ece |title=New U2 album No Line On The Horizon given lukewarm reception|newspaper=[[The Times]]|publisher=Times Newspapers Limited|first=Adam|last=Sherwin|authorlink=Adam Sherwin|date=2009-03-03|accessdate=2010-05-19}}</ref> For the band, ''Achtung Baby'' was a watershed that ensured their creative future,<ref name="finish" /> and its success prefigured their continued musical experimentation during the 1990s. ''Zooropa'', released in 1993, was a further departure for the band, incorporating additional dance music influences and electronic effects into their sound.<ref name="zooropa">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,307144,00.html |title=Zooropa |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |issue=178 |first=David |last=Browne |authorlink=David Browne |date=1993-07-09 |accessdate=2009-10-14}}</ref> In 1995, U2 and Brian Eno collaborated on the [[experimental music|experimental]]/[[ambient music|ambient]] album ''[[Original Soundtracks 1]]'' under the pseudonym "Passengers".<ref name="closer-to-edge" /> For ''[[Pop (album)|Pop]]'' in 1997, the group's experiences with [[dance club]] culture and their usage of [[tape loop]]s, [[programming (music)|programming]], rhythm [[Music sequencer|sequencing]], and [[Sampling (music)|sampling]] resulted in their most dance-oriented album.<ref name="closer-to-edge" />

The group's reinvention occurred at the peak of the alternative rock movement, when the genre was achieving widespread mainstream popularity. Bill Flanagan pointed out that many of U2's 1980s contemporaries struggled commercially with albums released after the turn of the decade. He argued that U2, however, were able to take advantage of the alternative rock movement and ensure a successful future by "set[ting] themselves up as the first of the new groups rather than the last of the old".<ref>Flanagan (1996), p. 213</ref> [[Toby Creswell]] echoed these sentiments in his 2006 music reference book ''[[1001 Songs]]'',  writing that the album helped U2 avoid "becoming parodies of themselves and being swept aside by the grunge and techno revolutions".<ref>Creswell (2006), pp. 377<U+2013>378</ref>  A 2010 retrospective by ''Spin'' said that "U2 became the emblematic band of the alternative-rock era with ''Achtung Baby''."

''Achtung Baby'' has been acclaimed as one of the greatest albums in rock history, and many publications have placed it among their rankings of the best records. Two years after the record's release, ''Entertainment Weekly'' placed it at number 28 on its list of the "100 Best CDs".<ref>{{cite magazine |title=100 Best CDs|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=1993-11-05|issue=195}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' collated worldwide data in 1997 from a range of renowned critics, artists, and radio [[DJ]]s, who placed the record at number 71 in the list of the "100 Best Albums Ever".<ref>{{cite news |title=100 Best Albums Ever|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|format=''Features'' insert|date=1997-09-19}}</ref> VH1 ranked it at number 65 on their "100 Greatest Albums of Rock & Roll" countdown from their series ''[[The Greatest (TV series)|The Greatest]]''.<ref>{{cite episode|title=100 Greatest Albums of Rock & Roll|series=[[The Greatest (TV series)|The Greatest]]|network=[[VH1]]|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=62190|number=042|airdate=2001-01-16}}</ref> In 2003, ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the record at number 62 on its list of "[[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]", writing, "U2 visibly loosened up on ''Achtung Baby'', cracking jokes and even letting themselves be photographed in color".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/6862/35223/35539|title=The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=2003-12-11|issue=937|accessdate=2010-04-20|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5mRK6HHHc|archivedate=2009-12-31}}</ref> That same year, "The Definitive 200" album list<U+2014>sponsored by the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]<U+2014>listed ''Achtung Baby'' at number 45.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080802040323/http://www.rockhall.com/pressroom/definitive-200/ |title=Definitive 200 |publisher=[[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] |author=[[National Association of Recording Merchandisers]] |accessdate=2009-12-27}}</ref> The ''Q'' staff named it the third-best album from 1980<U+2013>2004,<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Music That Changed the World: Top 20 Albums from 1980<U+2013>2004 |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |date=2004-03}}</ref> and similarly, in 2008, ''Entertainment Weekly'' called it the third-best album of the previous 25 years.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20207076_20207387_20207337,00.html |title=The New Classics: Music <U+2013> The 100 best albums from 1983 to 2008 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=2008-06-27|accessdate=2010-06-14|issue=999<U+2013>1000}}</ref> In 2006, the record appeared on a number of lists, including ''[[Hot Press]]''{{'}}s "100 Greatest Albums Ever" at number 21,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://hotpress.com/archive/2860544.html |title=Achtung Baby (21/100 Greatest Albums Ever) |magazine=[[Hot Press]] |date=2006-04-13|accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref> and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s "The All-Time 100 Albums".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/0,27693,Achtung_Baby,00.html |title=The All-Time 100 Albums: Achtung Baby |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=Josh |last=Tyrangiel|authorlink=Josh Tyrangiel|date=2006-11-13 |accessdate=2009-09-11}}</ref> In 2010, the record topped ''Spin''{{'}}s list of the "125 Best Albums of the Past 25 Years", which ranked the most influential albums in the 25 years since the magazine launched. The magazine wrote, "Unlike [[Radiohead]] with ''[[OK Computer]]'' and ''[[Kid A]]'', U2 took their [[post-industrial music|post-industrial]], trad-rock disillusionment not as a symbol of overall cultural malaise, but as a challenge to buck up and transcend. [...] Struggling to simultaneously embrace and blow up the world, they were never more inspirational."<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.spin.com/spin25/125-best-albums-past-25-years#page=14 | title = 125 Best Albums of the Past 25 Years: 1 <U+2013> U2, Achtung Baby | magazine = [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] | first = Charles | last = Aaron | date = 2010-04-22 | accessdate = 2010-04-23}}</ref>

